\ql\li0\fi0\ri-26656{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0
\par}\pard
\ql\li0\fi0\ri-26656{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0 Turning the grid lines on is useful for narrowing down an enemy }
\ql{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0 ship's point of origin. The ship's {\ul starting coordinates}{\v starting_coordinates } (ie. A5, D3) }
\ql{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0 are given to the left of the ship on the warp path, and with the grid }
\ql{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0 lines on you can see which planets are in that sector.   By noting }
\ql{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0 how far along the warp path an enemy ship has gone, you can }
\ql{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0 guess where it might be headed and prepare accordingly.  Once }
\ql{\f0\fs24\cf0\up0\dn0 you have researched the warp scanner, however, you will have a }
